data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which gives a clear failure message instead of an `InvalidCastException` if the type is wrong:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- A wrong type produces a readable test failure (`Assert.IsInstanceOfType failed`) instead of an unhandled `InvalidCastException`.
- The generic overload `IsInstanceOfType<T>` (MSTest v2.2.8+) avoids passing `typeof(...)` manually.

If you only need the type check and don't need `handler.Type`, you can drop the cast entirely.
